ion that race and race-based discrimination are over and no longer affect people’s everyday lives—to refute postracialism itself. In a world where they’re often written off as stereotypical “Angry Black Women,” Joseph offers that some Black women in media use “strategic ambiguity,” deploying the failures of post-racial discourse to name racism and thus resist it.In Postracial Resistance, Joseph listens to and observes Black women as they perform and negotiate race in strategic ambiguity. Using three methods of media analysis—textual readings of the media's representation of these women; interviews with writers, producers, and studio executives; and audience ethnographies of young women viewers—Joseph maps the tensions and strategies that all Black women must engage to challenge the racialized sexism of everyday life, on- and off-screen.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2021) 0aAfrican American womenxSocial conditions. 0aAfrican Americans and mass media. 0aMass media and women. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh  aAngry Black Women.  aFeminist.  aHollywood.  aMichelle Obama.  aOprah Winfrey.  aOprah.  aPostfeminist.  aShonda Rhimes.  aWinfrey.  ablack women.  acelebrity.  adiscrimination.  agender.  amedia.  aperforming race.  apostrace.  arace and media.  aracial ambiguity.  aracial equality.  aracial representation.  awomen in media.  awomen of color.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNew York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311072274140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479818426423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781479818426.jpg  a978-3-11-072274-1  New York University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL